## State Management with Hooks

### useState for Local State

Use `useState` for component-local state (not global application state):

```typescript
// Good: Local state with explicit types
const [formData, setFormData] = useState<CandidateFormData>(initialData);
const [isLoading, setIsLoading] = useState<boolean>(false);
const [error, setError] = useState<string | null>(null);

// Bad: Relying on type inference without explicit type
const [formData, setFormData] = useState(initialData);  // Unclear type
```

### useEffect for Side Effects

Always include dependency arrays:

```typescript
// Good: Explicit dependencies
useEffect(() => {
    const loadCandidates = async () => {
        try {
            const data = await candidateService.findAll();
            setCandidates(data);
        } catch (error) {
            setError('Failed to load candidates');
        }
    };
    
    loadCandidates();
}, []);  // Runs once on mount

// Bad: Missing dependency array (runs every render)
useEffect(() => {
    const loadCandidates = async () => { /* ... */ };
    loadCandidates();
});

// Bad: Missing dependencies (stale closure)
useEffect(() => {
    console.log(userId);  // userId not in dependency array
}, []);
```

### useCallback for Expensive Operations

Memoize callbacks to prevent unnecessary child re-renders:

```typescript
// Good: Memoized callback
const handleChange = useCallback((field: keyof FormData, value: string) => {
    setFormData(prev => ({ ...prev, [field]: value }));
}, []);

// Use in child component
<CandidateField onChange={handleChange} />
```

